---

🚀 Mini Practice Program

```python id="practice_os_pathlib"
from pathlib import Path

folder = Path("PythonNotes")

folder.mkdir(
    exist_ok=True
)

file = folder / "notes.txt"

file.write_text(
    "Python Directory Management"
)

print(
    file.read_text()
)
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

🔧 Best Practices

✔ Prefer `pathlib` for new projects
✔ Check file existence before operations
✔ Use `exist_ok=True`
✔ Handle exceptions properly
✔ Use absolute paths when necessary

---

⚠️ Common Mistakes

❌ Deleting files without checking existence
❌ Hardcoding file paths
❌ Forgetting permissions
❌ Mixing path separators manually
❌ Not handling exceptions

---

🧠 Interview Answer (Simple)

> The `os` module provides functions for interacting with the operating system, while `pathlib` offers a modern object-oriented way to manage files and directories. `pathlib` is generally preferred for new Python projects because it is cleaner and easier to use.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📚 Key Takeaways

✔ `os` interacts with files and directories
✔ `os.getcwd()` gets current directory
✔ `os.listdir()` lists files
✔ `pathlib` provides modern path handling
✔ `Path.exists()` checks file existence
✔ `Path.mkdir()` creates directories
✔ `pathlib` is preferred in modern Python development

